<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spur</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spur
<hw>Spur</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>spure</ets>,
<ets>spore</ets>, AS. <ets>spura</ets>, <ets>spora</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>spoor</ets>, G. <ets>sporn</ets>, OHG. <ets>sporo</ets>, Icel.
<ets>spori</ets>, Dan. <ets>spore</ets>, Sw. <ets>sporre</ets>, and to
AS. <ets>spor</ets> a trace, footstep, <ets>spyrian</ets> to trace,
track, examine, and E. <ets>spurn</ets>. ⟦root⟧171. Cf.
<er>Sparrow</er>, <er>Spere</er>, <er>Spoor</er>, <er>Spurn</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An implement secured to the heel, or above the heel, of
a horseman, to urge the horse by its pressure. Modern spurs have a small
wheel, or rowel, with short points. Spurs were the badge of
knighthood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And on her feet a pair of <qex>spurs</qex> large.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- To earn one's spurs, win one's spurs, to earn recognition for
achievement or for expertise. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which goads to action; an incitement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fame is the <qex>spur</qex> that the clear spirit doth raise⟦br⟧
(That last infirmity of noble mind)⟦br⟧
To scorn delights and live laborious days.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Something that projects; a snag.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One of the large or principal roots of a tree.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any stiff, sharp spine, as on the
wings and legs of certain birds, on the legs of insects, etc.;
especially, the spine on a cock's leg.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A mountain that shoots from any other mountain, or
range of mountains, and extends to some distance in a lateral direction,
or at right angles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A spiked iron worn by seamen upon the bottom of the
boot, to enable them to stand upon the carcass of a whale, to strip off
the blubber.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>A brace strengthening a post and
some connected part, as a rafter or crossbeam; a strut.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The short wooden
buttress of a post.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A projection from the round
base of a column, occupying the angle of a square plinth upon which the
base rests, or bringing the bottom bed of the base to a nearly square
form. It is generally carved in leafage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any projecting
appendage of a flower looking like a spur.</def> <au>Gray.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Ergotized rye or other grain.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A wall that crosses a part of a
rampart and joins to an inner wall.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A piece of
timber fixed on the bilge ways before launching, having the upper ends
bolted to the vessel's side.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A curved piece of
timber serving as a half beam to support the deck where a whole beam can
not be placed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A branch of a vein.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>The track of an animal, as an otter; a
spoor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spur fowl</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of
several species of Asiatic gallinaceous birds of the genus
<gen>Galloperdix</gen>, allied to the jungle fowl. The males have two or
more spurs on each leg.</cd> -- <col><b>Spur gear</b></col>
<fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a cogwheel having teeth which project radially
and stand parallel to the axis; a spur wheel.</cd> -- <col><b>Spur
gearing</b></col>, <cd>gearing in which spur gears are used. See under
<er>Gearing</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Spur pepper</b></col>.
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See the Note under <er>Capsicum</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Spur wheel</b></col>. <cd>Same as <cref>Spur gear</cref>,
above.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spur</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spur
<hw>Spur</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spurred</conjf> <pr>(sp⟦ucir⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spurring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To prick with spurs;
to incite to a more hasty pace; to urge or goad; <as>as, to
<ex>spur</ex> a horse</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To urge or encourage to action, or to a more
vigorous pursuit of an object; to incite; to stimulate; to instigate; to
impel; to drive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love will not be <qex>spurred</qex> to what it loathes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To put spurs on; <as>as, a <ex>spurred</ex>
boot</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spur</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Spur
<hw>Spur</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To spur on one's horse; to travel
with great expedition; to hasten; hence, to press forward in any
pursuit.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Now <xex>spurs</xex> the lated traveler.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Parthians shall be there,⟦br⟧
And, <qex>spurring</qex> from the fight, confess their fear.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The roads leading to the capital were covered with multitudes of
yeomen, <qex>spurring</qex> hard to Westminster.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some bold men, . . . by <qex>spurring</qex> on, refine
themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spurgall</ent>⟦br⟧
